s://web.archive.org/web/20090410022453/http://www.futbolas.lt/lt/lygos/a-lyga futbolas.lt] {{in lang|lt}}''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Pos.\n!Player\n!Club\n!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=1 align=\"center\"|1\n| {{flagicon|LTU}} [[Valdas Trakys]]\n| [[FK Ekranas|Ekranas]]\n|rowspan=1 align=\"center\"|20\n|-\n|rowspan=3 align=\"center\"|2\n| {{flagicon|LTU}} [[Tadas Kijanskas]] \n| [[FK V\u0117tra|V\u0117tra]]\n|rowspan=3 align=\"center\"|11\n|-\n| {{flagicon|LTU}} [[Mantas Kuklys]]\n| [[FK \u0160iauliai|\u0160iauliai]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|LTU}} [[Ri\u010dardas Beniu\u0161is]]\n| [[FK S\u016bduva|S\u016bduva]]\n|-\n|rowspan=1 align=\"center\"|5\n| {{flagicon|LTU}} [[Egidijus Varnas]] \n| [[FK Ekranas|Ekranas]]\n|rowspan=1 align=\"center\"|10\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|6\n| {{flagicon|LTU}} [[Povilas Luk\u0161ys]]\n| [[FK S\u016bduva|S\u016bduva]]\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|9\n|-\n| {{flagicon|LTU}} [[Mindaugas Grigalevi\u010dius]] \n| [[FK V\u0117tra|V\u0117tra]]\n|-\n|rowspan=3 align=\"center\"|8\n| {{flagicon|NGR}} [[Israel Awenayeri Douglas]] \n| [[FK Banga Garg\u017edai|Banga]]\n|rowspan=3 align=\"center\"|8\n|-\n| {{flagicon|LTU}} [[Igoris Morinas]]\n| [[FK Kruoja Pakruojis|Kruoja]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|LTU}} [[Andrius Urb\u0161ys]]\n| [[FK S\u016bduva|S\u016bduva]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{A Lyga seasons}}\n{{2008\u201309 in European football (UEFA)}}\n{{2009\u201310 in European football (UEFA)}}\n\n[[Category:LFF Lyga seasons]]\n[[Category:2009 in Lithuanian football|1]]\n[[Category:2009\u201310 in European association football leagues|Lith]]\n[[Category:2008\u201309 in European association football leagues|Lith]]\n", "name_user": "Jolicnikola", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLeague table", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2009_A_Lyga"}
{"title_page": "Claudio Grossman", "text_new": "{{update|date=November 2016}}\n{{Spanish name|Grossman|Guiloff}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name        = Claudio Grossman\n| image       = \n| caption     = Dean Nelson at AUWCL Tenley Campus\n| order       = 17th\n| title       = Dean of the [[Washington College of Law|American University Washington College of Law]]\n| term_start  = July 1995\n| term_end    = July 25, 2016\n| predecessor = Elliott Milstein\n| successor   = [[Camille A. Nelson]]\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1947|11|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Valpara\u00edso]], [[Chile]]\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| alma_mater  = [[University of Chile]]<br>[[University of Amsterdam]]\n| residence   = \n| spouse      = Irene Klinger\n}}\n'''Claudio Mauricio Grossman Guiloff''' (born November 26, 1947) is a [[lawyer]] and [[law professor]]. From 1995 until the summer of 2016, he served as [[Dean (education)|dean]] of the [[Washington College of Law]] of [[American University]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] He continues to teach at the Washington College of Law and serve as Dean Emeritus. In November 2016, he was elected to the [[United Nations International Law Commission]] for a five-year term. Grossman has also served as vice chair of the [[United Nations Committee Against Torture]] (2003-2008) and as Chairperson (2008-2015). He is a former member of the [[Inter-American Commission on Human Rights]] (1993-2001). He was twice elected its president, first in 1996 and again in 2001. He was the IACHR's first Special Rapporteur on the Rights of Women (1996-2000), as well as its Special Rapporteur on the Rights of Indigenous Populations (2000-2001).\n\nGrossman was born in Valpara\u00edso, Chile. He attended the [[law school]] at the [[University of Chile]] in Santiago. He received his Licenciado en Ciencias Jur\u00eddicas y Sociales in March 1971, with a ''[[Latin honors|summa cum laude]]'' [[thesis]] \"Nacionalizaci\u00f3n y Compensaci\u00f3n,\" coauthored with Carlos Portales.\n\nGrossman served as a [[lecturer]] in the University of Chile's Faculty of Law in 1972 and as a [[research fellow]] at the Instituto de Estudios Internacionales (Institute of [[International studies|International Studies]] at the University of Chile in 1973.  \n\nFrom 1974-1980 Grossman was [[associate professor]] in [[international law]] at the Department of International Organizations of the Europa Institute of the Law School of the [[University of Utrecht]] in [[the Netherlands]]. In August 1980 Grossman earned the ''Doctor in de Rechtsgeleerdheid'' (Doctor of the Science of Law) at the [[University of Amsterdam]]. His thesis was ''Het Beginsel van Non-Interventie in de Organizatie van Amerikaanse Staten'' (The Principle of [[Non-intervention|Non-Intervention]] in the [[Organization of American States]]). \n\nFrom 1980-1983, Grossman was professor in [[international law]] at the Department of Law, [[Universiteit Twente]].\n\nHe is a member of the [[Crimes Against Humanity Initiative]] Advisory Council, a project of the [[Whitney R. Harris World Law Institute]] at [[Washington University in St. Louis | Washington University School of Law in St. Louis]] to establish the world\u2019s first treaty on the prevention and punishment of crimes against humanity.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.wcl.american.edu/dean/cv.cfm Curriculum Vitae: Claudio Grossman]\n*[http://www.wcl.american.edu/faculty/grossman/ Faculty Profile: Claudio Grossman]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grossman, Claudio}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Chilean emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Chilean people of German descent]]\n[[Category:Anti-torture activists]]\n[[Category:Chilean human rights activists]]\n[[Category:American human rights activists]]\n[[Category:Members of the United Nations Committee against Torture]]\n[[Category:People from Santiago]]\n[[Category:American legal scholars]]\n[[Category:Chilean officials of the United Nations]]\n\n{{US-legal-academic-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{update|date=November 2016}}\n{{Spanish name|Grossman|Guiloff}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name        = Claudio Grossman\n| image       = \n| caption     = Dean Nelson at AUWCL Tenley Campus\n| order       = 17th\n| title       = Dean of the [[Washington College of Law|American University Washington College of Law]]\n| term_start  = July 1995\n| term_end    = July 25, 2016\n| predecessor = Elliott Milstein\n| successor   = [[Camille A. Nelson]]\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1947|11|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Valpara\u00edso]], [[Chile]]\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| alma_mater  = [[University of Chile]]<br>[[University of Amsterdam]]\n| residence   = \n| spouse      = Irene Klinger\n}}\n'''Claudio Mauricio Grossman Guiloff''' (born November 26, 1947) is a [[lawyer]] and [[law professor]]. From 1995 until the summer of 2016, he served as [[Dean (education)|dean]] of the [[Washington College of Law]] of [[American University]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] He continues to teach at the Washington College of Law and serve as Dean Emeritus. In November 2016, he was elected to the [[United Nations International Law Commission]] for a five-year term. Grossman has also served as vice chair of the [[United Nations Committee Against Torture]] (2003-2008) and as Chairperson (2008-2015). He is a former member of the [[Inter-American Commission on Human Rights]] (1993-2001). He was twice elected its president, first in 1996 and again in 2001. He was the IACHR's first Special Rapporteur on the Rights of Women (1996-2000), as well as its Special Rapporteur on the Rights of Indigenous Populations (2000-2001).\n\nGrossman was born in Valpara\u00edso, Chile. He attended the [[law school]] at the [[University of Chile]] in Santiago. He received his Licenciado en Ciencias Jur\u00eddicas y Sociales in March 1971, with a ''[[Latin honors|summa cum laude]]'' [[thesis]] \"Nacionalizaci\u00f3n y Compensaci\u00f3n,\" coauthored with Carlos Portales.\n\nGrossman served as a [[lecturer]] in the University of Chile's Faculty of Law in 1972 and as a [[research fellow]] at the Instituto de Estudios Internacionales (Institute of [[International studies|International Studies]] at the University of Chile in 1973.  \n\nFrom 1974-1980 Grossman was [[associate professor]] in [[international law]] at the Department of International Organizations of the Europa Institute of the Law School of the [[University of Utrecht]] in [[the Netherlands]]. In August 1980 Grossman earned the ''Doctor in de Rechtsgeleerdheid'' (Doctor of the Science of Law) at the [[University of Amsterdam]]. His thesis was ''Het Beginsel van Non-Interventie in de Organizatie van Amerikaanse Staten'' (The Principle of [[Non-intervention|Non-Intervention]] in the [[Organization of American States]]). \n\nFrom 1980-1983, Grossman was professor in [[international law]] at the Department of Law, [[Universiteit Twente]].\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.wcl.american.edu/dean/cv.cfm Curriculum Vitae: Claudio Grossman]\n*[http://www.wcl.american.edu/faculty/grossman/ Faculty Profile: Claudio Grossman]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grossman, Claudio}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Chilean emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Chilean people of German descent]]\n[[Category:Anti-torture activists]]\n[[Category:Chilean human rights activists]]\n[[Category:American human rights activists]]\n[[Category:Members of the United Nations Committee against Torture]]\n[[Category:People from Santiago]]\n[[Category:American legal scholars]]\n[[Category:Chilean officials of the United Nations]]\n\n{{US-legal-academic-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Freyarhianne", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claudio_Grossman"}
{"title_page": "List of satirists and satires", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{more citations needed|date=November 2008}}\n{{Dynamic list| date=March 2018}}\nBelow is an incomplete list of writers, cartoonists and others known for their involvement in [[satire]] \u2013 humorous social criticism. They are grouped by era and listed by year of birth. Also included is a list of modern satires.\n\n==Early satirical authors==\n*[[Aesop]] (c. 620\u2013560 BCE) \u2013 ''[[Aesop's Fables]]''\n*[[Diogenes]] (c. 412\u2013323 BCE)\n*[[Aristophanes]] (c. 448\u2013380 BCE) \u2013 ''[[The Frogs]]'', ''[[The Birds (play)|The Birds]]'', and '' [[The Clouds]]''\n*[[Gaius Lucilius]] (c. 180\u2013103 BCE)\n*[[Horace]] (65\u20138 BCE) \u2013 ''[[Satires (Horace)|Satires]]''\n*[[Ovid]] (43 BCE \u2013 17 CE) \u2013 ''[[Ars Amatoria|The Art of Love]]''\n*[[Seneca the Younger]] (c. 4 BCE \u2013 65 CE) \u2013 ''[[Apocolocyntosis]]''\n*[[Persius]] (34\u201362 CE)\n*[[Petronius]] (c. 27\u201366 CE) \u2013 ''[[Satyricon]]''\n*[[Juvenal]] (1st to early 2nd centuries CE) \u2013 ''[[Satires (Juvenal)|Satires]]''\n*[[Lucian]] (c. 120\u2013180 CE)\n*[[Apuleius]] (c. 123\u2013180 CE) \u2013 ''[[The Golden Ass]]''\n*''Various authors'' (9th century CE and later) \u2013 ''[[One Thousand and One Nights]]''\n<!-- While, in the current usage, each of these authors and works can be said to be satirical, it should be kept in mind that satire per se was a formal genre invented by the Romans. Of this list only Lucilius, Horace, Persius, and Juvenal actually wrote satire. \u2013 Nefasdicere -->\n\n==Medieval, early modern and 18th-century satirists==\n*[[Godfrey of Winchester]] (d. 1107)\n*[[Ubayd Zakani]] (died 1370) \u2013 ''Akhlaq al-Ashraf (Ethics of the Aristocracy)''\n*[[Giovanni Boccaccio]] (1313\u20131375) \u2013 ''[[The Decameron]]''\n*[[Geoffrey Chaucer]] (c. 1343\u20131400) \u2013 ''[[The Canterbury Tales]]''\n*[[Gil Vicente]] (c. 1465\u20131536)\n*[[Desiderius Erasmus]