x.php/phrenology-history-of-a-pseudoscience/ ''Phrenology: History of a Classic Pseudoscience''] - by [[Steven Novella]] MD\n* [http://skepdic.com/phren.html The Skeptic's Dictionary] by [[Robert Todd Carroll]]\n\n{{Pseudoscience}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Phrenology| ]]\n[[Category:Biological anthropology]]\n[[Category:Criminology]]\n[[Category:History of astrology]]\n[[Category:History of neuroscience]]\n[[Category:History of psychology]]\n[[Category:Human head and neck]]\n[[Category:Philosophy of mind]]\n[[Category:Physiognomy]]\n[[Category:Pseudoscience]]\n", "name_user": "GyanChodu", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:Fix Rwanda Genocide reference link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phrenology"}
{"title_page": "Callahan Tunnel", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Refimprove|date=April 2009}}\n{{Infobox tunnel\n|name    = Callahan Tunnel\n|image    = Callahan-tunnel-boston-ma-usa.jpg\n|caption   = The entrance to the tunnel just past I-93 Southbound Exit 24B to Logan Airport.\n|location  = [[Boston, Massachusetts]]\n|coordinates = \n|route    = {{jct|state=MA|MA|1A|dir1=north}}\n|status   = Open\n|start    = [[Downtown Boston]]\n|end     = [[East Boston]]\n|startwork  = \n|opened = {{start date and age|November 11, 1961}}\n|close    = \n|owner    = [[Commonwealth of Massachusetts]]\n|operator  = [[Massachusetts Department of Transportation]]\n|character  = \n|construction= high-strength steel and concrete infill\n|length   = {{convert|.96|mi|km|abbr=on}}\n|lanes    = 2\n|speed    = {{convert|40|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}\n|hielevation = \n|lowelevation= \n|height   = {{convert|13.4|ft|m|abbr=on}}<ref name=june02_russell.pdf>{{cite journal | url=http://www.icri.org/publications/2002/PDFs/mayjune02/CRBMayJune02_Russell.pdf | title=Rehabilitation of the Sumner/Callahan Tunnels | publisher=International Concrete Repair Institute, Inc. | work=Concrete Repair Bulletin | date=May\u2013June 2002 | accessdate=May 7, 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131230235752/http://www.icri.org/publications/2002/PDFs/mayjune02/CRBMayJune02_Russell.pdf | archivedate=December 30, 2013 }}</ref>\n|width    = {{convert|24.2|ft|m|abbr=on}}<ref name=june02_russell.pdf/>\n|grade    = \n|toll    = Between $0.20 and $2.05 depending on payment method and residency\n}}\n\nThe '''Lieutenant William F. Callahan Jr. Tunnel''' (colloquially '''Callahan Tunnel''') is one of four [[tunnel]]s, and one of three road tunnels, beneath [[Port of Boston|Boston Harbor]] in [[Boston, Massachusetts]]. It carries motor vehicles from the [[North End, Boston|North End]] to [[Logan International Airport]] and [[Massachusetts Route 1A|Route 1A]] in [[East Boston]]. Ordinarily, this tunnel is only used to carry traffic out of the city, and with the completion of the [[Big Dig]] it only collects traffic from [[Interstate 93|I-93]] southbound (right after traffic merges from Storrow Drive) and downtown Boston. As of 2016, a [[Toll tunnel|toll]] of $1.50 is charged for non-commercial two-axle vehicles with a Massachusetts E-ZPass, while non-Massachusetts E-ZPass holders are charged $1.75. Vehicles without E-ZPass are charged $2.05 through MassDOT's Pay By Plate MA program. For residents of certain Boston ZIP codes, a discount is in effect using an [[E-ZPass]] transponder, costing $0.20.\n\n==Alternatives==\n\nTraffic flowing between Logan International Airport and directions south of the city on I-93 and west of the city on the [[Massachusetts Turnpike]] (I-90) normally uses the [[Ted Williams Tunnel]] rather than the Callahan and Sumner Tunnels. Airport traffic can also use East Boston surface roads to and from Chelsea ([[Chelsea Street Bridge]]), Revere ([[Massachusetts Route 1A]]) and Winthrop ([[Massachusetts Route 145]]).\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Callahan Tunnel.png|thumb|left|Map showing the Callahan Tunnel (in red)]]\n\nThe tunnel was opened in 1961. It was named for the son of Turnpike chairman [[William F. Callahan]], who was killed in [[Italy]] days before the end of World War II. Operatic tenor William Flavin, of Milton, Massachusetts, sang [[The Star-Spangled Banner]] and [[Danny Boy]] at the opening of the Callahan Tunnel in 1961.\n\nIn 2016, [[Open road tolling|cashless tolling]] systems were installed in both directions, entering the Sumner Tunnel and exiting the Callahan Tunnel as part of a plan to modernize toll collection the Boston area.<ref>{{cite web|title=Toll Rates|url=https://www.ezdrivema.com/TollCalculator|website=EZDRIVEMA|accessdate=December 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHistorically, control signals were used to reverse the direction of one lane in this tunnel or the Sumner Tunnel, when the opposite tunnel was closed for maintenance or emergencies. Under the relevant Turnpike regulations, a yellow signal light means \"proceed only as directed\", on penalty of a $50 fine. As the signals are almost always yellow, this rule is universally ignored by drivers.{{citation needed|date=December 2013}} Other markings in the tunnel include a \"double white line\" in the center, intended to discourage drivers from changing lanes, to be penalized with a $100 fine.\n\nThe Callahan Tunnel was repaired in the 1990s.<ref name=\"Callahan Tunnel closure begins at 11 p.m.\">{{cite news | last=Hanson | first=Melissa | title=Callahan Tunnel closure begins at 11 p.m. | url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2013/12/27/callahan-tunnel-closing-begins-friday/eCLWjIjgfmXAzTzlwzmYGM/story.html | work=Boston Globe | date=December 27, 2013 | accessdate=December 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\nA major overhaul began in December 2013, which completely replaced the deck, curbs, and wall panels; and cleaned and repaired its ceiling and vent systems (above the ceiling and below the deck). It was planned for three phases: complete closure from December 27, 2013 to March 12, 2014 during deck and curb replacement; closures 11pm-5am from March 13, 2014 to late August 2014 for wall panel replacement; and final work until November 2014. McCourt Construction of South Boston was awarded the $19.3 million contract in August.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.bizjournals.com/boston/blog/mass_roundup/2013/11/callahan-tunnel-closing-for-three-months.html?page=all | title=Here's what you need to know about the Callahan Tunnel's three-month closure | last=Chesto | first=Jon | work=Boston Business Journal | date=November 17, 2013 | accessdate=March 31, 2014}}</ref> During closures, Logan-bound traffic was diverted into the [[Ted Williams Tunnel]], [[Tobin Bridge]], and [[Massachusetts Route 1A]] South via Revere or East Boston.<ref name=\"massdot\">{{cite web | url=http://www.massdot.state.ma.us/highway/HighlightedProjects/CallahanTunnelRehabilitationProject.aspx | accessdate=December 30, 2013 | title=Callahan Tunnel Rehabilitation Project | work=Massachusetts Department of Transportation}}</ref> Starting with the Accelerated Bridge Program in the late 2000s, MassDOT began employing accelerated construction techniques, in which it signed contracts with incentives for early completion and penalties for late completion, and used intense construction during longer periods of complete closure to shorten the overall project duration and reduce cost.<ref>{{cite journal | url=http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/publications/publicroads/12mayjune/03.cfm | title=The Fast 14 Project | last=Moran | first=Jack | work=Public Roads | date=May\u2013June 2012 | volume=75 | issue=6 | publisher=United States Federal Highway Administration}}</ref> These techniques were also used for the Callahan Tunnel Rehabilitation Project.<ref name=\"massdot\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n{{commons category}}\n* [[Sumner Tunnel]]\n* [[Ted Williams Tunnel]]\n* [[Thomas P. O'Neill Jr. Tunnel]]\n* [[Massachusetts Turnpike]]\n* [[Zakim Bunker Hill Bridge]]\n* [[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority|MBTA]]'s [[East Boston Tunnel]]\n\n{{coord|42|22|04|N|71|2|46|W|type:landmark_region:US|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Boston Harbor]]\n[[Category:Road tunnels in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Tunnels in Boston]]\n[[Category:U.S. Route 1]]\n[[Category:Interstate 93]]\n[[Category:Tunnels completed in 1961]]\n[[Category:Toll tunnels in Massachusetts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=April 2009}}\n{{Infobox tunnel\n|name        = Callahan Tunnel\n|image       = Callahan-tunnel-boston-ma-usa.jpg\n|caption     = The entrance to the tunnel just past I-93 Southbound Exit 24B to Logan Airport.\n|location    = [[Boston, Massachusetts]]\n|coordinates = \n|route       = {{jct|state=MA|MA|1A|dir1=north}}\n|status      = Open\n|start       = [[Downtown Boston]]\n|end         = [[East Boston]]\n|startwork   = \n|opened = {{start date and age|November 11, 1961}}\n|close       = \n|owner       = [[Commonwealth of Massachusetts]]\n|operator    = [[Massachusetts Department of Transportation]]\n|character   = \n|construction= high-strength steel and concrete infill\n|length      = {{convert|.96|mi|km|abbr=on}}\n|lanes       = 2\n|speed       = {{convert|40|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}\n|hielevation = \n|lowelevation= \n|height      = {{convert|13.4|ft|m|abbr=on}}<ref name=june02_russell.pdf>{{cite journal | url=http://www.icri.org/publications/2002/PDFs/mayjune02/CRBMayJune02_Russell.pdf | title=Rehabilitation of the Sumner/Callahan Tunnels | publisher=International Concrete Repair Institute, Inc. | work=Concrete Repair Bulletin | date=May\u2013June 2002 | accessdate=7 May 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131230235752/http://www.icri.org/publications/2002/PDFs/mayjune02/CRBMayJune02_Russell.pdf | archivedate=30 December 2013 }}</ref>\n|width       = {{convert|24.2|ft|m|abbr=on}}<ref name=june02_russell.pdf/>\n|grade       = \n|toll        = Between $0.20 and $2.05 depending on payment method and residency\n}}\n\nThe '''Lieutenant William F. Callahan Jr. Tunnel''' (colloquially '''Callahan Tunnel''') is one of four [[tunnel]]s, and one of three road tunnels, beneath [[Port of Boston|Boston Harbor]] in [[Boston, Massachusetts]]. It carries motor vehicles from the [[North End, Boston|North End]] to [[Logan International Airport]] and [[Massachusetts Route 1A|Route 1A]] in [[East Boston]]. Ordinarily, this tunnel is only used to carry traffic out of the city, and with the completion of the [[Big Dig]] it only collects traffic from [[Interstate 93|I-93]] southbound (right after traffic merges from Storrow Drive) and downtown Boston. As of 2016, a [[Toll tunnel|toll]] of $1.50 is charged for non-commercial two-axle vehicles with a Massachusetts E-ZPass, while non-Massachusetts E-ZPass holders are charged $1.75. Vehicles without E-ZPass are charged $2.05 through MassDOT's Pay By Plate MA program. For residents of certain Boston ZIP codes, a discount is in effect using an [[E-ZPass]] transponder, costing $0.20.\n\n==Alternatives==\n\nTraffic flowing between Logan International Airport and directions south of the city on I-93 and west of the city on the [[Massachusetts Turnpike]] (I-90) normally uses the [[Ted Williams Tunnel]] rather than the Callahan and Sumner Tunnels.  Airport traffic can also use East Boston surface roads to and from Chelsea ([[Chelsea Street Bridge]]), Revere ([[Massachusetts Route 1A]]) and Winthrop ([[Massachusetts Route 145]]).\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Callahan Tunnel.png|thumb|left|Map showing the Callahan Tunnel (in red)]]\n\nThe tunnel was opened in 1961. It was named for the son of Turnpike chairman [[William F. Callahan]], who was killed in [[Italy]] days before the end of World War II. Operatic tenor William Flavin, of Milton, Massachusetts, sang [[The Star-Spangled Banner]] and [[Danny Boy]] at the opening of the Callahan Tunnel in 1961.\n\nIn 2016, [[Open road tolling|cashless tolling]] systems were installed in both directions, entering the Sumner Tunnel and exiting the Callahan Tunnel as part of a plan to modernize toll collection the Boston area.<ref>{{cite web|title=Toll Rates|url=https://www.ezdrivema.com/TollCalculator|website=EZDRIVEMA|accessdate=2 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nHistorically, control signals were used to reverse the direction of one lane in this tunnel or the Sumner Tunnel, when the opposite tunnel was closed for maintenance or emergencies. Under the relevant Turnpike regulations, a yellow signal light means \"proceed only as directed\", on penalty of a $50 fine. As the signals are almost always yellow, this rule is universally ignored by drivers.{{citation needed|date=December 2013}} Other markings in the tunnel include a \"double white line\" in the center, intended to discourage drivers from changing lanes, to be penalized with a $100 fine.\n\nThe Callahan Tunnel was repaired in the 1990s.<ref name=\"Callahan Tunnel closure begins at 11 p.m.\">{{cite news | last=Hanson | first=Melissa | title=Callahan Tunnel closure begins at 11 p.m. | url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2013/12/27/callahan-tunnel-closing-begins-friday/eCLWjIjgfmXAzTzlwzmYGM/story.html | work=Boston Globe | date=27 December 2013 | accessdate=28 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nA major overhaul began in December 2013, which completely replaced the deck, curbs, and wall panels; and cleaned and repaired its ceiling and vent systems (above the ceiling and below the deck).  It was planned for three phases: complete closure from December 27, 2013 to March 12, 2014 during deck and curb replacement; closures 11pm-5am from March 13, 2014 to late August 2014 for wall panel replacement; and final work until November 2014.  McCourt Construction of South Boston was awarded the $19.3 million contract in August.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.bizjournals.com/boston/blog/mass_roundup/2013/11/callahan-tunnel-closing-for-three-months.html?page=all | title=Here's what you need to know about the Callahan Tunnel's three-month closure | last=Chesto | first=Jon | work=Boston Business Journal | date=17 November 2013 | accessdate=31 March 2014}}</ref> During closures, Logan-bound traffic was diverted into the [[Ted Williams Tunnel]], [[Tobin Bridge]], and [[Massachusetts Route 1A]] South via Revere or East Boston.<ref name=\"massdot\">{{cite web | url=http://www.massdot.state.ma.us/highway/HighlightedProjects/CallahanTunnelRehabilitationProject.aspx | accessdate=30 December 2013 | title=Callahan Tunnel Rehabilitation Project | work=Massachusetts Department of Transportation}}</ref>  Starting with the Accelerated Bridge Program in the late 2000s, MassDOT began employing accelerated construction techniques, in which it signed contracts with incentives for early completion and penalties for late completion, and used intense construction during longer periods of complete closure to shorten the overall project duration and reduce cost.<ref>{{cite journal | url=http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/publications/publicroads/12mayjune/03.cfm | title=The Fast 14 Project | last=Moran | first=Jack | work=Public Roads | date=May\u2013June 2012 | volume=75 | issue=6 | publisher=United States Federal Highway Administration}}</ref>  These techniques are also being used for the Callahan Tunnel Rehabilitation Project.<ref name=\"massdot\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n{{commons category}}\n* [[Sumner Tunnel]]\n* [[Ted Williams Tunnel]]\n* [[Thomas P. O'Neill Jr. Tunnel]]\n* [[Massachusetts Turnpike]]\n* [[Zakim Bunker Hill Bridge]]\n* [[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority|MBTA]]'s [[East Boston Tunnel]]\n\n{{coord|42|22|04|N|71|2|46|W|type:landmark_region:US|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Boston Harbor]]\n[[Category:Road tunnels in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Tunnels in Boston]]\n[[Category:U.S. Route 1]]\n[[Category:Interstate 93]]\n[[Category:Tunnels completed in 1961]]\n[[Category:Toll tunnels in Massachusetts]]\n", "name_user": "Oknazevad", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript, update tense", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Callahan_Tunnel"}
{"title_page": "Mehdi Hashemi (actor)", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Mehdi Hashemi<br/>{{lang|fa|\u0645\u0647\u062f\u06cc \u0647\u0627\u0634\u0645\u06cc}}\n| image = Mehdi Hashemi at 32th Fajr.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption = Mehdi Hashemi at [[Fajr International Film Festival|32nd Fajr]]\n| birth_name = Mir Mehdi Hashemi Ghermezi\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1946|12|07}}\n| birth_place = [[Langarud]], [[Iran]]\n| occupation              = [[Actor]], [[Screenwriter]], and [[Film director|Director]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| othername     = \n| alma_mater = [[University of Tehran]]\n| residence = [[Tehran]]<br/>[[Lahijan]]\n| nationality = [[Iran]]ian\n| yearsactive   = 1969\u2013present\n| spouse        = {{marriage|[[Golab Adineh]]|1981}}<br/>[[Mahnoosh Sadeghi]]\n| children      = 1\n| notable role =\n| awards = [[Fajr Film Festival]] best actor (1991)\n}}\n'''Mehdi Hashemi''' ({{lang-fa|\u0645\u0647\u062f\u06cc \u0647\u0627\u0634\u0645\u06cc}}, also [[Romanize]]d as '''Mehd\u012b H\u0101shem\u012b''', {{IPA-fa|meh\u02c8di\u02d0 h\u0252\u02d0\u0283e\u02c8mi\u02d0}}, born 7 December, 1946) is an [[Iran]]ian [[actor]], [[screenwriter]], and [[Film director|director]].\n\nHe also is the winner of the ninth [[International Fajr Film Festival]] award, [[Crystal Simorgh]], for his playing in the film ''Do Film Ba Yek Belit'' (translates \"one ticket for two movies\").\n\nHe is the husband of Iranian actress, [[Golab Adineh]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.mehrnews.com/news/14852/24th-Fajr-filmfest-to-pay-tribute-to-actress-Adineh-and-composer|title=24th Fajr filmfest to pay tribute to actress Adineh and composer Entezami|date=2006-01-16|website=Mehr News Agency|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>, and brother of Nasser Hashemi. \n\n==Selected filmography==\n*''Zende bad'' (Long Live) (1979)\n*''[[Death of Yazdgerd (film)|Death of Yazdgerd]]'' (1982)\n*''Kharej az mahdudeh'' (1986)\n*''Bo